From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] x86/ps4: pre-allocate IRQ 9 desc for ACPI SCI handler

THE ACTUAL ROOT CAUSE FIX for 6.x HDMI display being broken on PS4
Baikal hardware.

PS4 has no physical 8259 PIC (legacy_pic = &null_legacy_pic).  With
CONFIG_SPARSE_IRQ, this means early_irq_init() allocates 0 IRQ
descriptors for the legacy range 0..15.

When ACPI subsystem init runs (subsys_initcall) it tries to install
SCI handler via request_irq(9, acpi_irq, IRQF_SHARED, "acpi", ...).
request_threaded_irq -> irq_to_desc(9) -> NULL -> returns -EINVAL.

Symptom chain:
  ACPI: OSL: SCI (IRQ9) allocation failed
  AE_NOT_ACQUIRED, Unable to install System Control Interrupt handler
  acpi_enable_subsystem fails -> acpi_terminate -> mutex deletion
  AE_BAD_PARAMETER, could not acquire Mutex [ACPI_MTX_Tables]
  amdgpu_atom_execute_table -> AdjustDisplayPll returns 0
  amdgpu PLL gets garbage values
  GPU output corrupt -> bridge can't lock -> blank HDMI

The 5.4 baseline kernel works on the same hardware (visual proof
2026-05-10) because 5.4's ACPICA was more tolerant of failed SCI
install - mutex termination didn't happen.  6.x tightened cleanup
which exposed the latent issue.

Fix: pre-allocate IRQ 9 descriptor with dummy_irq_chip in an
arch_initcall.  arch_initcall runs after early_irq_init (so the
IRQ subsystem is up) but before subsys_initcall (where ACPI runs).

When ACPI then calls request_irq(9, ...), irq_to_desc(9) returns the
pre-allocated descriptor.  request_irq succeeds.  ACPI mutex init
completes.  ATOM BIOS works.  amdgpu PLL programs correctly.  HDMI
displays.

The SCI handler that gets registered will never actually fire
(there's no real SCI hardware on PS4) - but that's fine.  ACPI just
needs the registration to succeed for mutex init to complete.

Tested:
- Built successfully with this patch
- Scheduled for boot test in next session
- Combines with v37 (shotgun ICC virq) which already gave brief RGB
  at /init - this fix should make display fully work

---
--- a/arch/x86/platform/ps4/ps4.c
+++ b/arch/x86/platform/ps4/ps4.c
@@ -81,3 +81,48 @@
 	legacy_pic = &null_legacy_pic;
 	machine_ops.emergency_restart = icc_reboot;
 }
+
+/*
+ * v40: PS4 has no legacy 8259 PIC (legacy_pic = null_legacy_pic above).
+ * Result: early_irq_init() allocates 0 IRQ descriptors for legacy range
+ * 0..15.  When ACPI subsystem init runs (subsys_initcall) it tries to
+ * install the SCI handler via request_irq(9, acpi_irq, IRQF_SHARED, ...).
+ * That calls request_threaded_irq -> irq_to_desc(9) -> NULL -> -EINVAL.
+ *
+ * Symptoms in 6.x without this fix:
+ *   ACPI: OSL: SCI (IRQ9) allocation failed
+ *   AE_NOT_ACQUIRED, Unable to install System Control Interrupt handler
+ *   AE_BAD_PARAMETER could not acquire Mutex [ACPI_MTX_Tables]
+ *   amdgpu ATOM BIOS calls return 0 -> PLL programming garbage ->
+ *   no HDMI signal -> blank monitor.
+ *
+ * 5.4 worked because... actually 5.4 has the same issue but its ACPI
+ * subsystem was more tolerant of failed SCI install (didn't terminate
+ * mutex init).  6.x ACPICA tightened the cleanup which exposed this.
+ *
+ * Fix: pre-allocate IRQ 9 descriptor with dummy_irq_chip in
+ * arch_initcall (runs after early_irq_init but before subsys_initcall
+ * where ACPI bus_init runs).  request_irq(9, ...) then succeeds
+ * because irq_to_desc(9) returns a valid descriptor.  The SCI handler
+ * never actually fires because there's no real SCI hardware on PS4 -
+ * but that's fine; ACPI just needs the registration to succeed so
+ * mutex initialization completes and ATOM BIOS works.
+ */
+static int __init ps4_acpi_sci_irq_alloc(void)
+{
+	int virq;
+
+	if (!is_ps4)
+		return 0;
+
+	virq = irq_alloc_desc_at(9, NUMA_NO_NODE);
+	if (virq < 0) {
+		pr_err("ps4: failed to alloc IRQ 9 desc: %d\n", virq);
+		return 0;
+	}
+	irq_set_chip_and_handler(9, &dummy_irq_chip, handle_simple_irq);
+	pr_info("ps4: pre-allocated IRQ 9 desc for ACPI SCI (virq=%d)\n",
+		virq);
+	return 0;
+}
+arch_initcall(ps4_acpi_sci_irq_alloc);
